   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:p text:style-name="Title"><text:span text:style-name="T1">Intoduction: </text:span>Formation of kanji</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P1">Total number of kanji <text:span text:style-name="T2">is over </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">100,000; They </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">were</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3"> coined back in the days in China, </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">and is the top among all languages when it comes to characters amount</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">In elementary school<text:span text:style-name="T3">, </text:span>you learn about a thousand characters of that<text:span text:style-name="T3">, </text:span>and about doubled amount of characters for daily life.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3">In this article, we try to categorize kanjis into 4 different type<text:span text:style-name="T6">s</text:span> based on their formation.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P4" text:outline-level="1">Pictogram</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">These are characters originated from <text:span text:style-name="T7">and trying to mimic</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T8">the </text:span>shape and appearance of real life objects.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr1" draw:name="枠1" text:anchor-type="char" svg:width="11.09cm" draw:z-index="0">
